Cook,<br>
I think that a key issue to the whole discussion we have is the question of Vietnam, and whether or not it was one nation or two. <br><br>
If it was one nation, the war was basically a civil war. Our rights to intervene are different than if it is a war between nations. <br><br>
My view is that it was a civil war, between forces in Vietnam and we did not have the right to enter into the war. Our entry was based on the call for help from a non-representative government. <br><br>
You ask...<br>
&quot;Why are the South Vietnamese citizens without a country today? &quot; They never had a country, only a temporary division. One of the things both sides wanted was reunification, albeit under differnet circumstances.<br><br>
You say.. &quot;Perhaps we could have done more had we had our fellow countrymens support.&quot;  Perhaps we could have done more if we looked to a solution that was based on diplomatic efforts and economic aid. If we put 1/2 the money and resources into an economic solution what do you think Vietnam would look like today?<br><br>
You say.. &quot;Perhaps if we hadn't had to fight communist supported demonstations and dis-information at home many Americans would not have lost heart for the plea of the South Vietnamese citizen. &quot; Perhaps if we had a cause that people could ralley around we would have made another kind of effort that would have succeeded.<br><br>
You say..  Tell me, Where is the freedom to determine their own fate the invading North Vietnamese Army (NVA) promised the South Vietnamese citizens?  Wish I understood why after the war there was such a repressive reaction on the part of the North. You won't find me supporting that. Not now, not ever. I get a sense that things are changing now in VN. Don't have facts to support that, only glimpses trying to read between the lines of newspaper reports. Anyone out there have a sense about the current status of VN concerning repression / freedom?
